work_experience.description:
Stewarded LaMP through a growth trajectory from a working group based at a think tank to a fully-fledged organization already demonstrating momentum;
Forged several new agreements both with governments and industry actors, creating concrete proof of concept for mobility at scale;
Established LaMP operations across 25+countries and six continents; 
Generated over $10 million committed from external funders;
Established enduring partnerships with a wide variety of needed stakeholders, including governments, large retailers, industry actors, and worker representatives.

Pioneered a new approach of plurilateral partnerships between national governments and industries as the solution to unlocking labor mobility;
Led the exploratory design and set-up of a new organization, Labor Mobility Partnerships (LaMP);
Developed and tested the theory of change via analysis and consultations with key stakeholders;
Managed the Connecting International Labor Markets working group consultative process;
Secured and delivered on specific engagements to pilot LaMPs services.

Designed a pilot using results-based financing to open a labor migration corridor between Afghanistan and the GCC countries, the first such program ever designed in the World Bank; 
Prepared assessments of the sending system in Afghanistan and market analysis of prospective receiving countries for Afghan labor;
Designed and delivered a technical assistance program for the Ministry of Labor on managed migration.

Prepared policy reports on several technical aspects of international labor migration (including regulation of recruitment, labor integration of refugees, and admission systems);
Designed a framework for assessing sending country systems and applied this framework to institutional gap assessments for several sending countries;
Fed these assessments into the design of tailored technical assistance aimed at addressing these gaps in the countries labor sending systems;
Contributed to technical assistance for Saudi Arabia and Malaysia on their labor receiving systems.

Drafted the initial World Bank response for private sector recovery in Sierra Leone during the ebola crisis, which resulted in immediate interventions being implemented on the ground;
Produced a technical report on potential designs for a business incubator in the nascent ICT sector in Gabon, which was later fed into country dialogue;
Produced the final second phase report for the Government of Sierra Leone on the Sierra Leone Growth Poles program, and contributed to the production of the final first phase report.
